Right-wing populists triumph in Austria, up 29 percent
According to the first preliminary results, the early parliamentary elections in Austria brought a noticeable weakening of the two parties of the previous grand coalition and a significant strengthening of the right-wing populist parties.
Particularly strong losses were suffered by the Austrian People's Party, where the position of the current chairman, Wilhelm Molterer, is seriously shaken.
On the other hand, the electoral leader of the Union for the Future of Austria (BZI), the Carinthia governor, Jurg Haider, is preparing a triumphant return to national politics.
According to preliminary results, it remains the strongest party in the country's Social Democracy (SPP) with 29.8 percent of the vote, but against the last election in 2006, it loses 5.5 percent of the vote.
Even worse was the VP, which lost with 25.6 percent to almost nine percent of the vote.
These are the worst results of both of these major parties in Austria’s post-war history, and especially for the people who triggered the early elections, a literally disastrous result.
Even at the beginning of July, when the VP left the coalition, the people had a significant advantage over the SP.
However, voters have apparently punished them for letting the government crash.
Already in the first reactions to the results, there was speculation about the possible resignation of the party chairman and former vice-chancellor Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers believe this could happen as early as Monday at an emergency meeting of the party's presidency.
Such a development would probably facilitate the way to the still most likely way out of the election result, i.e. the resumption of the grand coalition of the SSP and the PDP.
However, due to the strengthening of both right-wing populist parties - the Free Party (FPO) - they provisionally won 18 percent of the vote and the BZ - eleven percent of the vote - at the same time, the Social Democrats expressed concern about a repeat of 1999, when the People's Party agreed with the populists (at that time the FPO was still united, in 2005 it split from the BZ - split) on the joint government, which even provoked sanctions from the European Union.
Haider, who has already said he is ready to work with any party and expects a return to Vienna for national politics, seems to be betting on this development.
The Green Party also entered parliament, but it lost slightly and fell from third to fifth place among Austrian political parties.
None of the other parties apparently broke the 4% threshold and did not make it to parliament.
