The bottom is bigger than the land
Today, the coastal states began to apply vehemently for new underwater territories.
Under the United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea, they are exercising their rights, which were agreed in 1982 in Montego Bay, Jamaica.
This is mainly the area of the so-called continental shelf, which often extends up to several hundred kilometers from the coast of the country.
It has exclusive rights under the Convention to all resources of the continental shelf.
"Simply put, the continental shelf is that part of the seabed and its subsoil which is the natural continuation of the continent under the sea.
It reaches beyond the borders of the coastal sea, often even beyond the border of two hundred nautical miles of the so-called exclusive economic zone,” explains Mikulka.
The application submitted by the country concerned to the Commission for the demarcation of the external borders of the continental shelf shall be supported by comprehensive scientific and technical documentation based on a number of costly surveys and measurements.
It is the result of many years of preparatory work.
"One of our tasks is to provide the Commission with legal and technical assistance.
To date, the Commission has examined five applications from Russia, Brazil, Australia, Ireland and New Zealand.
