But New Zealand has also gained - the area of the seabed, which the commission granted him last week, is about 1.6 million square kilometers, about six times the size of the state itself.
Both countries invested millions of dollars in the survey.
The profits that will flow from the use of the seabed in the future will be, as they promise, invaluable.
Other countries will also submit their applications gradually.
They can do so up to ten years after they have ratified the Montego Bay Convention.
Where the continental shelf ends, the ocean floor area begins, declared by convention to be the "common heritage of mankind".
No country has an exclusive position anymore.
The mining right in this area is granted by an international institution established by the Convention.
"The seabed is not a Klondike", says director Mikulka in exaggeration, adding that his "individual areas are legally clearly defined and their regime contractually enshrined".
