Travel agents record growing numbers of bookings
It looks like winter will be good for German businessmen in tourism:
According to one study, travel bookings for the coming months increased significantly compared to the previous year - even by more than 30 percent for the winter season.
Despite weak economic growth, the desire of the Germans to travel remains undisturbed.
For winter season bookings, travel agencies saw a 31% increase in turnover compared to the same period last year, according to the Deutsche Reiseverband (DRV) in Berlin on Monday.
According to a survey by the market research institute GfK, there are already increased numbers of reservations available for the autumn months.
According to the DRV, the turnover for October was about 11 percent higher compared to 2007.
The basis for these results is the GfK figures, which evaluates reservation data from 1,200 German travel agencies each month and interpolates them into the overall market.
This result included travel bookings that took place until the end of August 2008.
Due to the weak dollar, trips to the US are in demand, the DRV said.
For these trips, the increase in reservations is about one-third.
In addition, Spain, Turkey and Greece are particularly desirable destinations for Germans, as well as domestic waters.
In particular, organized tours are on course, said DRV chairman Klaus Laepple.
With regard to rising energy and food expenses, the costs are "easier for the client to calculate than for an individually organized holiday".
Laepple explained that consumers can save money by, among other things, taking advantage of early booking discounts or all-inclusive offers.
Even in the summer months, the number of reservations was very good, so there will be a higher turnover again compared to the previous year - although according to another study, the number of Germans taking a trip has decreased compared to the previous year.
