Turkey's Diplomatic Horizons Expand
Long before Turkey began its bid to join the European Union, European powers longed to penetrate deep into the Turkish hinterland.
On the east bank of the Bosporus, perhaps only twenty steps in Asia, stands one of the best monuments of this failed imperial ambition.
Hydarpaša railway station was designed by two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in the Neo-Renaissance style.
Tourist guides will tell you that.
The building sits astride the end of platforms with a tower on each corner of the facade, a sight indistinguishable from any provincial German town hall.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building is slowly falling apart.
But once one gets inside the vault, one can no longer doubt the size of the enterprise whose westernmost gate the station was.
The station was opened in August 1908 by the German consortium Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, which joined the empires late, intended to implement its ambitions for control of the Middle East by means of this railway, which was to lead to Damascus, Baghdad and beyond in what is now Saudi Arabia.
But German imperial ambitions collapsed during World War I.
Their tracks were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular troops.
The relative isolation from the surrounding territories, created by the frozen borders of the Cold War, is gone.
British and colonial troops advanced out of Egypt and drove the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
And there was bad news for the Hydarpasha station as well.
In 1917, an ammunition train blast destroyed her elaborate roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then, they have been gradually crumbling and history has been bypassing it.
Today, however, this gateway to Anatolia and further east serves - at least symbolically - to highlight the expanding horizons of Turkish diplomacy.
The ruling Justice and Development Party - AKP - has created a completely new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from the surrounding territories, created by the frozen borders of the Cold War, is gone.
Now a new policy is in place - Turkey is getting involved.
It is remarkable that the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
In order to review the parameters of this new policy, I boarded a night train to the Turkish capital Ankara, where I was to meet one of the AKP’s leading foreign policy experts, Turkish MP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning - about ten and a half hours later - after a bumpy ride on the tracks that reminded the old-world rhythms of the famous Night Mail documentary, I arrived in the Turkish metropolis, designed as a new city for a secular state that wants to turn its back on its Ottoman past.
However, the AKP, with its well-known Islamist roots, represents a paradigm shift of the Turkish consensus.
It raised suspicions in the West, especially in Washington.
The taxi took me to the AKP's main tent, an ultramodern stone and metal building, purposely built in an emerging suburb, surrounded by half-built department stores and power dealers, where middle managers in business suits - both men and women - meet to make early morning deals.
Suat Kiniklioglu could easily be a centre-right politician from almost any other European political party.
Jacket, tie, I'm sure he had a Blackberry.
"The aim of the party's foreign policy is to reintegrate Turkey into its immediate vicinity.
“The Cold War was an anomaly,” he said.
Turkey has been cut off from its borders.
You have to look east and west at the same time.
It wasn't a choice.
He had to do both.
"But there will certainly come a time," I asked, "when might Turkey have to decide?"
"Turkey," he said, "didn't want such a decision to have to be made."
He then emphasized what almost everyone I spoke to said almost by heart: Turkey’s relations not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus and the Black Sea region are just as beneficial to Europe and the United States as to Turkey.
With Turkey on board, it seems that Europe as a whole can, metaphorically speaking, follow these tracks eastward into Asia and the Middle East.
Back at the Hydarpasha station, after another mostly sleepless night, I thought of the two German masters Herr Ritter and Herr Conu, who watched how this building was being built a hundred years ago.
How surprised they would be if they found out that European ambitions in the Middle East could now be, in large part, in Turkish hands.
And as I waited for the ferry back through the Bosphorus at the port, I remembered that in those days Turkey was called "the sick man of Europe".
So it seems that at least then there was little doubt as to which continent should be entitled to this fascinating land.
Memorable Lives: Vernon Handley and William Woodruff
Mark Brown writes: As Guildford's music supervisor since 1962, Vernon "Tod" Handley (an obituary, September 11) was in charge of the Guildford Philharmonic Orchestra and Choir.
As part of the district's musical plan, he established the excellent Proteus Youth Choir for a year.
He was supposed to be 21 years old, but by the time Proteus last sang in 1979, a few of us were almost 30 - we simply refused to give up that choir.
The name "Proteus" (mythological shapeshifter) represented the willingness and ability of the choir to engage in whatever music was presented to it - whether madrigals or Messiaen, either alone or with the whole orchestra.
The musical adaptability created by such a young choir was often overwhelming, always exciting, and all thanks to the inspiration of that one man and the enthusiasm for music that remained absolutely unchanged all the time.
How often did Tod tell us to "let the music speak for itself".
He said, "The composer knows what he wants.
It's all in the music.
Then sing it!"
His batting technique was perfectly clear and precise, but it was neither dictatorial nor flowery.
Wherever the standard of music was, it always raised it.
John Frayn Turner wrote:
If any conductor was to be knighted, it was Vernon Handley.
I knew him well in two decades when he conducted the Guildford Philharmonic from 1962 to 1982.
Over the past 40 years or so, I have reviewed more than 100 of his concerts, and I can honestly say that I have never been disappointed by any of them - and I have been inspired many times.
Tod Handley had such a great combination of size and personal modesty.
He hated conductors who, in his words, simply "pulled through the world one or two soaking stones".
He will be missed by many of us.
William Woodruff
Professor John Beckett writes:
Your obituary of William Woodruff (25 September) claims that "in 1946 he returned to economic history at Oxford and in 1950 he became a researcher at Houblon-Norman... while also studying for a BSc, MA and PhD".
This is based on Woodruff's comment by the author in Beyond Nab End, but it's not accurate.
From 1946 to 1953 he taught economic history at the University of Nottingham, and at that time completed a dissertation on the British rubber industry, led by Professor J. D. Chambers, and subsequently published it in 1958 as a publication of the British rubber industry.
He actually spent 1950-51 in America as a researcher at Houblon-Norman and the summer of 1952 at the University of Illinois, Harvard, and New York.
In 1953, he left Nottingham and moved to Illinois.
It is not known why Woodruff passed this part of his career.
