Honda will launch its best-seller for the second time
In November, Honda will begin selling the second generation Jazz.
If the predecessor of this one-space vehicle already had considerable space, it now offers an even more spacious interior.
Added to this are improved engines that increase driving comfort and allow for greater fuel efficiency.
Evolution rather than revolution.
This is the second generation of the Honda Jazz.
Although from an aesthetic point of view, the lines of the new Jazz are very similar to the previous model, there have been many changes on this one-space car.
It is necessary to mention, for example, innovative design, a new platform, larger dimensions and new engines.
Even before we explore the new model, it should be noted that the new Jazz comes to market six years after the launch of the first generation.
Therefore, the first thing we notice is that Honda needed a shorter period to rejuvenate this model than other manufacturers.
Although in Europe Jazz is a lesser-known model, in other markets it has become a phenomenon in sales.
This is the case in Japan, the country where the Jazz was the best-selling car in 2002 and also during 2008.
Almost one million units have been sold in Japan since the introduction of the Honda Jazz.
The second market became the old continent with about half a million units sold in six years.
Honda, however, aims to increase sales in its category with the new Jazz.
That is, while the Japanese company sold a total of 83,000 units of the Honda Jazz in 2007, in 2009 estimates count 100,000 cars, which would mean an increase of 17% in the European market.
As far as the Spanish market is concerned, Honda has sold a total of 8,000 units of the Jazz since 2002, accounting for 6.7% of Honda's total sales in Spain.
As for the new generation of Jazz, the management of the Spanish branch expects to sell 2,000 units for the whole year.
The arrival of the new Jazz will allow Honda to significantly mitigate the decline in sales in Spain.
As a result, the company’s management expects the year to end with a total of 22,000 units sold, which is 4,000 fewer than in 2007, and a 16% decrease.
Despite this increase in sales, Honda increased its share of the Spanish market to 1.8%, up from 1.6% last year.
In 2010, the Japanese company expects to reach 2%.
To achieve this share, Honda relies on the success of its next new model.
It is the Honda Insight, a five-door, compact-size hybrid with a length of 4.37 meters, from which the Japanese company promises worldwide sales of approximately 200,000 units per year.
In terms of markets, the Japanese manufacturer estimates that 50% of Insight will be sold in the United States, while the remaining percentage will be split between the old continent and Japan.
