Compared to the first generation, all dimensions of the new Jazz have increased.
Its length has increased to 3.9 metres (five centimetres more), its width to 1.69 metres (two centimetres more), and its wheelbase to 2.5 metres, which means an extension of five centimetres.
The height, on the other hand, has not changed and is still 1.52 meters.
The increase in dimensions has also increased the interior space.
This advantage was achieved both by using the new platform and by placing the fuel tank in the middle of the car, which was already used in the previous Honda Jazz.
Also, the luggage compartment volume - which has a double bottom system - increased to up to 399 liters, 19 liters more than the luggage compartment volume of the first generation.
It should be noted that these dimensions occur with the 1.4 engine version, since the luggage compartment volume of the Honda Jazz 1.2 is 379 liters.
In addition to the exterior features - such as rear LED lights or the possibility of equipping with a panoramic glass roof - it is easier to access the rear seats.
The doors leading to the second row of seats allow an opening angle of 80 degrees compared to 67 for the first Jazz model.
In the second generation of the Honda Jazz, there are also new engines.
Initially, this small model will be offered with two gasoline engines of 1.2 and 1.4 liters.
Both engines use i-VTEC technology, which allows for lower fuel consumption, lower carbon dioxide emissions and delivers outstanding improvements to the drive system at the same time with high torque in the full engine speed range.
The first 1.2 litre engine has 90 hp at 6,000 rpm with a maximum torque of 114 Nm at 4,900 rpm.
This engine - which had 78 hp on the previous generation Jazz - consumes 5.3 liters and emits 125 grams of CO2.
Compared to the previous engine, which in the previous generation reached 83 hp, the current one will reach 100.
Honda Jazz 1.4 with 100 hp has a combined consumption of 5.4 liters and emissions of 128 grams of CO2.
"Car bee" prevents collisions
This time, Nissan has been inspired by nature, specifically bees, to develop accident protection technologies.
This Japanese company has created a robot that takes the role of flying bees and thus prevents collisions.
This is Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which is the first step in rain prevention technologies.
Engineers at Nissan Motor Co.’s Center for Technological Advancement have developed the robot in collaboration with the Center for Advancement in Scientific and Technological Research at the prestigious Tokyo University.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, general manager of public relations for the brand's technology, research and development, the BR23C is presented as an extension of Nissan's four safety shield zones.
The robot’s task is to strengthen the collision prevention capabilities of the brand’s vehicles.
During the flight, each bee creates its own personal space of oval shape, which is very similar to the Nissan safety shield.
However, the most important are the compound bee eyes, which are able to see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees, allowing the bee to fly in its personal space without stopping.
In creating this visual function, the engineers designed what they called a Laser Range Finder.
It detects obstacles that are up to two meters in a 180-degree radius before BR23C, calculates the distance of the object and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately converts it to a collision warning.
"The moment an obstacle is detected, the robot mimics the bee's movements and immediately changes direction by turning the wheels to a right or even greater angle to prevent a collision.
The biggest difference from any existing system is that all evasive maneuvers are completely instinctive.
If this were not the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobile Laboratory and chief engineer of the project.
Unlike bees, the robot can not move up and down even diagonally, its movement is limited to only two dimensions and the direction that is made possible by the rotation of its wheels, but not in an infinite number of directions and possibilities as in bees.
In addition to acceleration and deceleration, Nissan also used the rotation function to prevent the robot from colliding.
"The device only needs to process the information every few seconds and to maintain itself according to this data.
It does not require information or logical intuition from previous maneuvers, so it can work without interruption with only two dozen kilobytes of memory.
It may surprise you, but we’re not talking about gigs or megas.”
This is the first step in the development of new technologies for instant collision prevention, a technology that Nissan predicts will be used in production cars in a decade.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion ones.
Another possible future use of this technology could be the integration of the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system, which would lead the driver to the destination while avoiding obstacles on the road.
