Rafael Correa in Quito on Monday.
Re-establishing a republic around 21st century socialism.
Such is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Eva Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
Last Sunday, the third nominee put to the vote, following the example of his counterparts and friends, the draft of a new Constitution.
And his mission is accomplished, as 64% of voters, according to official results covering 80% of the vote, voted 'yes' in the referendum.
"No" according to these results gained 28%, 7% of the votes were invalid and 0.7% of the ballots were empty.
In order for the bill to pass, it had to win half the votes plus one.
Two polls carried out at the exit of the polling stations and the count of NGOs predicted a clear "yes" victory on Sunday, placing them in the range of 63% to 70%.
Rafael Correa demanded the victory of his draft constitution on the night of Sunday.
"The Constitution has prevailed," he said, congratulating the Ecuadorians at the Guayaquil Governorate, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
It goes without saying that Rafael Correa received congratulations from Chávez and Morales, but also from his Chilean counterpart, Michelle Bachelet.
The vote, which took place peacefully according to the Organization of American States (OEA) observation mission, concerned a text on 444 points building a "new socialism" promoted by the president.
The draft Constitution sanctifies the power of the state over the economy by reserving to it the "planning of development" of the country living primarily from the extraction of oil by foreign companies and from the foreign exchange sent by its emigrants.
The proposal, backed by Correa, who was elected in 2006, also extends the powers of the head of state, who will be able to exercise two consecutive four-year mandates and be able to dissolve the House.
Correa has already announced that it will use this power and will seek a new mandate in February 2009.
Among other things, the constitution reinforces the principle of free health and education, which the president began to introduce in a country with 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
Finally, it also envisages banning the presence of foreign troops, ending the agreement between Washington and Quito to use the Ecuadorian base as the starting point for U.S. drug operations.
19 hostages freed in Chad
The Egyptian commando took 11 tourists and their eight-man escort who were captured ten days ago by an attack.
They're in Cairo.
Eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian guides, who were held captive in the desert for ten days, were brought to the Egyptian capital on Monday.
In the morning, they were liberated in Chad by an Egyptian commando.
The hostages arrived around 3.30 pm, apparently in good shape, aboard a special plane to al-Maza military base, closely adjacent to Cairo International Airport.
They were immediately taken, without being able to express themselves in the press, aboard helicopters to a hospital in Maadi, a peripheral residential district of Cairo, to undergo medical examinations there.
"They are completely healthy" and "no ransom has been paid to the hijackers," Egypt's tourism minister Zoheir Garrana said on the airport's runway.
Since its capture on September 19, during a safari in a four-wheel-drive vehicle at the foot of Mount Uanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, a group of hostages has been dragged from one hideout to another by 35 unknown hijackers.
The group includes 11 tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - as well as eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, one border guard of the director of the agency Aegyptous, the organizer of the safari.
A senior Egyptian security official suggested that 30 members of the special forces who approached the scene aboard two helicopters had taken to the jet during the night just before dawn.
"There was a shootout, half of the hijackers were killed and the others fled," said the source, who wished to remain anonymous.
He suggested that a total of 150 members of Egypt's special forces from the "flash" unit were sent to Sudan, where they gained the support of German and Italian commandos.
The head of Italian diplomacy, Franco Frattini, from Belgrade, mentioned the role played by secret agents and Italian special forces.
"We must recognize that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of people from our intelligence services, from special forces," he said.
He also denied that a ransom had been paid.
On the eve, the Sudanese military said it had detained a four-wheel-drive vehicle carrying the hijackers, killing six including a Chadian commander and arresting two.
The army claimed to have been linked to a rebel group in Darfur, the Sudan Liberation Movement - Unity (SLA-U), which the movement immediately rejected.
