the Governments of the Benelux State Bank Fortis
The Benelux countries will help the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis, which was the first in Europe to get into trouble due to the spreading effect of the US mortgage market crisis, partial nationalisation: three countries will support the monetary and insurance institution, which also has a capital participation in Hungary, with an amount of EUR 11.2 billion.
This was agreed at the highest level this weekend by the Belgian, Luxembourg and Dutch governments, with the participation of the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commissioner for Competition.
Bank Fortis is the first in the euro area to experience a major crisis as part of the international financial markets crisis, which has been spreading in waves for more than a year, and the decisions made on this matter could be seen as precedents in some respects.
According to the decision, which was born on Sunday night, all three states will buy almost half (49 percent) of the bank’s assets there.
The bank will sell part of its capital holdings, mainly insurance activities purchased last year from the Dutch bank ABN Amro.
Fortis shares began to fall sharply last week, and in the second half of the week there were already serious signs of the crisis in the institution.
But analysts agree that with its 85,000 employees, the bank is too big to let go of.
The company's securities fell 12% on Friday alone, to a 14-year low.
Since January, the value of shares has fallen by more than two-thirds.
Given the current share prices, the total market capital value of the group is around EUR 14 billion, but this is unrealistic, according to the company’s leaders.
Indeed, the company’s management blames the collapse of Fortis shares on the uncertainty in the overseas market related to the adoption of the US $700 billion package plan.
By Monday, the stock had risen slightly.
On Friday, new CEO Filip Dierckx was appointed to the head of the bank.
The financial institution was also looking for private buyers, but no one has yet applied with a more serious offer.
The Belgian government has previously announced that investors need not worry, they will not lose their money.
So far, there has been no panic among the bank’s clients, and the branches have not been taken by storm.
In Hungary, Fortis Bank has a separate branch and has also bought several leasing companies.
Fox in the chicken coop
Life and health insurance companies in America, based on people’s data about buying drugs, often reject the possibility of concluding an insurance contract with the applicant.
Data protection experts are concerned that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There is a data protection program that binds the use of prescribing data in any case to the consent of the person concerned.
It has to be in the hands of someone independent, otherwise we entrust the chicken coop to the fox," Richard Dick, author of a program designed to monitor prescriptions, told the Washington Post.
Insurance companies make premiums and amounts paid in the event of insurance claims dependent on the health status of the candidates, and if the risk is assessed as too great, they do not even take out insurance with it.
In the past, they sent people for medical examinations and concluded contracts only when they knew their results.
Ten years ago, Dick came up with a much cheaper procedure: based on the identification number, the pharmacy customer can easily find out what drugs the person has bought in the last year and a half, from which the program itself will deduce what kind of disease he is suffering and what is his state of health.
For example, if he regularly buys a large number of cholesterol-lowering drugs, this refers to having virtually uncontrollably high blood fat levels, which immediately puts him in a higher-risk category.
There are several versions of the program in circulation, some of which determine the risk coefficient at the same time, so that the insurance company has almost no work left except for paperwork, although minor difficulties arise.
The disadvantages include that some drugs can also be used for several purposes, some compounds are, for example, useful against migraines or hot flashes, but they are also effective against depression.
From the point of view of commercial insurance companies, these represent a significant risk-increasing factor, while the previously mentioned difficulties do not.
In order to request and process the data, special companies have been set up to ask for the patient’s consent before obtaining the necessary information from pharmacies.
They are now being forced to do so by the authorities, even though they have not been punished for their past negligence.
Recently, some companies are also processing the results of laboratory tests, which combine with data on the drugs used, thanks to which they can provide an even more accurate picture of the health status of patients.
More and more companies have access to data, and at the same time it will be more and more difficult to control their use.
There is a special law on the protection of health data, but its effectiveness applies only to health service providers and insurance companies.
The bill, which will give authorities the power to control even companies specializing in providing data, is before Congress.
Richard Dick acknowledges that this is not enough: therefore, he has developed his programme in such a way that the transfer of data is subject to the express consent of the person concerned.
Another thing is that he can hardly refuse the permission in question, otherwise the insurance companies will not conclude a contract with him.
So the chickens are somewhat reliant on the fox of good will after all.
