European Union and India to double trade turnover
As the European Union and India are each other’s leading trading partners, the agenda of the Ninth High Level Meeting has dominated this topic among other, mostly global, issues.
A Franco-Indian summit will also be held today, which will focus on cooperation in the field of nuclear energy.
The European Union recognises that India is an emerging democratic power that should be given greater opportunity to speak out in international affairs, but the member countries have not yet managed to find a common denominator in supporting New Delhi's permanent membership of the UN Security Council.
This question was not even further discussed at yesterday's ninth summit, held in Marseille.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, as the current President of the Union, and the President of the European Commission José Manuel Barroso and High Representative for Foreign Policy Javier Solana welcomed Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, with whom they also agreed that trade turnover will double in five years, or increase to more than one hundred billion euros.
