The rest of Steve Fossett's plane, a millionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007, while flying across the desert in Nevada, was found.
The debris was discovered on a single plateau at an altitude of 3,000 meters, in the Mammoth Lakes area of Sierra Nevada, on the border between California and Nevada.
However, there were no human remains inside the aircraft.
The Madera County sheriff, John Anderson, dismissed the doubts that remained: "The plane was found, we sent a team there and now we are sure that this is exactly what Steve Fossett was flying in on the day he disappeared," he said at a press conference.
The sheriff said no human remains were found on the plane or in the surrounding area.
A 63-year-old millionaire has been presumed dead since February.
The U.S. Transportation Safety Bureau (Ntsb) announced that hours after the debris was detected, an investigation team was dispatched to identify the plane: it was exactly the Bellanc 8kcab, missing since September 3, 2007, when Fossett took off from Yerington, Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, still in California, not far from the border with Nevada, some of Fossett's personal items were found by one couple near their dwelling in Mammoth Lakes.
These are two documents bearing Fossett's name, both issued by the Illinois Federal Aviation Administration, about cash and one jacket.
Fossett's search was interrupted a month after his disappearance.
